Content:
How can I show that $L_2\le L_1$ $||x||_1\ge ||x||_2$ and also we have that $\|x\|_2\leq \sqrt m\|x\|_{\infty}$ regarding the first part, can I say that: $$
\sqrt{\sum\limits_{i=1}^n x^2 } \leq {\sum\limits_{i=1}^n {\sqrt x}^2 }
$$

AcceptedAnswer:
I assume you are using finite dimensional vector spaces (looks like a familiar question from Golub and Van Loan). \begin{align}
||x||_2^{2}=\sum_{i=1}^{N}|x_i|^2\leq\left(\sum_{i=1}^{N}|x_i|^2+2\cdot\sum_{i,j,i< j}|x_i||x_j|\right)=||x||_1^2
\end{align} This implies $||x||_2\leq ||x||_1$ . Now \begin{align}
||x||_2^{2}=\sum_{i=1}^{N}|x_i|^2\leq N\cdot\max_{i}(|x_i|^2)=N||x||_{\infty}^{2}
\end{align} This implies $||x||_2\leq \sqrt{N}||x||_{\infty}$
